<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Cameron, Duncan. A sketch of the Customs, Manners, and Way of Living of the Natives, All the Quadrupeds, as Well as Birds, and Fishes, that are Found in the barren Country About Nipigon, <span class="AddHand-editors">[1804]</span>. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0026</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">N</span><sup>o</sup><span style="text-decoration:underline;"> 3</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">existence, which constitutes their only enjoyment, for<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> I have often seen them boil Tobacco and drink the juice of it, to keep them in that state of intoxication, when they could get so much more liquor.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Indians are, by nature, very ungrateful; for you may render them ever so many services, and bestow ever so much on them, the least thing they give you or do for you, must be paid for &#8211; they are the greatest and most shameless Beggars that ever existed; for give them ever so much, they will still continue to ask more, till you absolutely refuse them.  Some of them are great thieves, and all very deceitful, for when they pay us the credits we advance them, it is not any principle of honesty that makes them do it, but the good usage they receive, and for fear of being refused when in need again &#8211; they are very distrustful of us, for being themselves unacquainted with honour or honesty<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span></p>

